english:
  title: Record of the Fragrant Hall
  author: Lee Seok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Book of Poetry says: "Where shall I find the fragrant herb to plant behind my house?" The commentators explain: "This is the herb of forgetfulness." And the character dictionary likewise defines the fragrant herb as the herb that makes one forget sorrow. To call it by the character for "forget" speaks of forgetting one's cares; to derive it from the character for "open" speaks of clearing away what oppresses the heart. When what oppresses the heart is cleared away, the Way flows freely; when sorrow is forgotten, joy arises. In joy, one harmonizes with parents and they too rejoice. In this flowing freedom, one becomes one with heaven and earth, and heaven and earth achieve balance. When heaven and earth are balanced and parents are joyful—this is the governance of Yao and Shun in their age of peace, which mortals can scarcely attain. Seek the principle underlying this, and you find it in natural form; seek the form, and you discover it in this single plant. One humble thing, one modest character—yet through them shine forth the principles of heaven and the feelings of humanity, the very structure of good governance and the spirit of the realm.

    I have long pondered these matters with kindred spirits. One day, my student Yom Jeong-su, whose courtesy name is Min-mang, came and said: "My elder brother named his dwelling 'Chrysanthemum Slope,' my middle brother named his 'Eastern Pavilion.' I, though unworthy, have fortunately passed the examinations, and because three sons of our house have done so, the state has granted sustenance to our mother. My three brothers share one breath and one heart. In all our dwelling and movement, we observe and admonish one another, desiring only to pursue goodness. Presuming too much upon myself, I wish to call my dwelling 'Fragrant Hall.' I humbly ask you to explain its meaning."

    Hearing this, I cited the Poetry and briefly explained the characters. Now I elaborate further: Heaven and earth are breath and vital force. People and things receive this force to be born. They divide into groups, gather by kind, flow toward moisture and seek the dry, appearing chaotic without yet remaining inwardly ordered and resplendent with principle, never once disordered. The gentleman in youth reads and investigates things, illuminating the principles of all affairs under heaven. In maturity he serves his lord and orders all things, bringing the principles of all under heaven into harmony. In such vastness, what can trouble his vital force? In such contentment, what can wound his heart? When principle flows gently and doubt melts like ice, how could even a hair's breadth of discord remain between them?

    Min-mang, though youngest in years, is richest in learning, and has companied with the literary masters of our time, embodying the great image of the hexagram of Difficulty. Thus his resolve is deep without falling into empty wandering, his practice earnest without galloping toward distant illusions. Turning back to seek within his own heart, he knows neither sorrow nor oppression. He merely serves heaven and earth, serves his parents, and extends this service to his lord, wishing that abundant grain and precious herbs fill every field and garden. Surely such devotion reaches far indeed. Does not the opening verse say: "O noble brother, jewel of our land"? The jewel of the land possesses no other talent or virtue than this: to accord with parents, to flow with heaven and earth, to witness in one's own person the governance of Yao and Shun. Min-mang, strive onward.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The fragrant herb (Hemerocallis) was traditionally associated with maternal care and the alleviation of sorrow in East Asian culture.
  - key: ''
    value: Yao and Shun represent the ancient sage-kings of China, whose era of perfect governance served as the ideal model for Confucian political philosophy.
  - key: ''
    value: The hexagram of Difficulty (坎) refers to the I Ching (Book of Changes), suggesting the student has mastered its wisdom.
  - key: ''
    value: This text is a letter of instruction and encouragement, written in the literary format of classical Chinese prose-poetry.
